<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,652,1130]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,328,730,756]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[422,496,730,756]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1189,1213]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,198,1165]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,197,1165]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Adults of Exaeretia spp.: 1, E. liupanshana Wang, sp. nov. (paratype, 3); 2, E. lechriosema (Meyrick); 3, E. indubitatella (Hannemann); 4, E. ciniflonella (Lienig &amp; Zeller)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/294034/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number box="[480,496,730,756]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
) with wingspan 19.5−22.0 mm. The species is characterized by the forewing having two conspicuous short rectangular discal and discocellular stigmata. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Stainton" authorityName="Stainton" box="[1203,1436,768,794]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Exaeretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="allisella">
<emphasis box="[1203,1331,768,793]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">E. allisella</emphasis>
Stainton
</taxonomicName>
in the female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[432,520,805,831]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,272,1282,1306]" captionTargetBox="[189,1423,261,1248]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,261,1259]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 11. Female genitalia of Exaeretia spp: 9, E. liupanshana Wang, sp. nov. (paratype, genitalia slide no. ZL 08245); 10, E. lechriosema (Meyrick); 11, E. indubitatella (Hannemann)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/294036/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number box="[488,520,805,831]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished by the valva somewhat truncate dorsoapically, and the juxta with clavate-shaped lateral lobe in the male genitali (
<figureCitation box="[909,985,842,868]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,274,1587,1611]" captionTargetBox="[172,1375,327,1551]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,309,1564]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. Male genitalia of Exaeretia spp.: 5, E. liupanshana Wang, sp. nov. (holotype, genitalia slide no. ZL 08247); 6, E. lechriosema (Meyrick); 7, E. indubitatella (Hannemann); 8, E. ciniflonella (Lienig &amp; Zeller)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/294035/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number box="[967,985,842,868]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authority="Stainton" authorityName="Stainton" box="[1041,1284,842,868]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Exaeretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="allisella">
<emphasis box="[1041,1174,842,867]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">E. allisella</emphasis>
Stainton
</taxonomicName>
, the valva is rounded or gently arched dorsoapically, and the lateral lobe of juxta is narrowly elongate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,652,1130]" box="[196,782,917,943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,356,917,943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Distribution.</emphasis>
Chian (Xinjiang), Russian Far East.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,652,1130]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,273,954,980]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Notes.</emphasis>
The adults and male genitalia of the specimens collected in Xinjiang were compared with those of the 
<typeStatus box="[196,305,992,1018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">lectotype</typeStatus>
deposited in the Natural History Museum, London (
<collectionCode box="[935,1031,992,1018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">BMNH</collectionCode>
). Small differences were found in the scale coloration of the forewing and in the shape of the distal process of the sacculus in the male genitalia. However, taking specimen abrasion and the locality into consideration, we still consider this species as 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Exaeretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lechriosema">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">E. lechriosema</emphasis>
(Meyrick)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
